snippet.textDisplay:
Love this play through! I am also surprised more youtubers haven't jumped on it yet. From being on a keto type diet, I've personally found that when I hit my macros correctly I tend to actually have dreams that I can remember those nights. May just be coincidence but having not had any dreams for years and now having them each time I've been on keto seems fishy. I also fully believe that at night during your rest is when cellular regeneration really can kick in. The whole idea of ketosis is to get the insulin levels to have smaller spikes when eating and the ketones to take back over faster, along with intermittent fasting I really think help the body in repairs at night. Especially if you time it to have your longer fasting times at night.


Just a fun thought on my experiences, love the vids guys and gals and thank you for keeping us entertained while locked up at home :)

snippet.textDisplay: Can confirm about the bug hallucination. I didn't sleep for a week because I had sleep paralysis every night as a kid that progressively got more and more terrifying. In class on about day 5 or 6 of not having any sleep, save for the occasional 4 or 5 minute fall asleep standing up moment, I saw a shadow that looked like a spider crawling across my desk heading towards the edge of my desk. I hit the desk really hard and hurt my hand, and my teacher and the other kids were confused (probably because I hit the desk almost at full force). I just said it was a bug and we moved on with the lesson. I don't remember much else about that week, except for going in and out of being cognitive. For example, I remember coming to on my back porch after falling asleep standing up,  but I don't remember the events before or shortly after that. I remember almost falling asleep at one point in the night and experiencing a terrifying sleep paralysis episode that was so realistic that I screamed until my throat was raw and everyone in the house had woken up. It was so weird because I only ever had sleep paralysis in my own house. If I slept at the neighbors I was fine, same for friends places too. I moved out of there over the summer and I haven't had an episode since.

snippet.textDisplay:
I wouldn't be surprised if we find out at the end that John is actually a "lab rat" himself. Those "brain damages" and memory loss could very much be inflicted by the Doctor. If we think a lot, in psychiatric facilities, before we had our current, more humaine treatments, some of the "techniques" used on patients, had to do with electricity and your brain. What if they did that to John, to either cure something...or to just test something on him. Many times, mentally ill patients were used as test subjects. The same goes for death row inmates.

The room we are in, could possibly be a replicate of his own room, to make the subject feel more at ease. The robot talking, could be a monitoring device.
They could be inducing the nightmares with a mix of some medicine. Playing with Serotonin and Neuroepinefrin could do that. Like in Until Dawn!! The brothers get treated for wrong illness, gets auditory and visual hallucinations. Same thing applies here, but it just happens on purpose...

Or it could just be a Theory!! 😁

snippet.textDisplay: It's crazy how real this stuff is. I've always delt woth insomnia, panic attacks, and anxiety. At one point in my later teens I decided to try and see how long I could stay awake. I went 7 days. Day 3 I started seeing glimpses of this monkey watching me from a far. He never came super close but he was always there. Then day 4 I went to a rock show to help stay awake and the music sounded distorted to me and it almost seemed like there were whispers under the tone of the music and they made me feel really off. Day 5  I was atba friends and they fell asleep and I laid there in the dark and it sounded like things were constantly tip toeing around me and though I couldn't see I felt that many things were watching me and stalking around me. Day 6 was really odd. A lot of things in my vision tunneled as if it was far away and I had an overwhelming feeling that I was constantly lost despite knowing where I was. Day 7 really sucked as everything from the previous days culminated and the panic was so intense and I heard what sounded like armies marching constantly and that monkey was always atleast 5 feet away hiding but watching, sounds were warped, things didn't appear as they should, and my mind really didn't know what was and wasn't real at times. Truly trippy and terrifying. I don't reccomend it and I would never do that experiment again. I didn't feel right for weeks afterwards.
